defs.docs: A statistics-driven micro-benchmarking library written in Rust.

defs.name: init_logging
defs.docs:
Initialize the logging for a Criterion benchmark. This should be called
 first before executing Criterion benchmarks, unless the user provides their
 own logging infrastructure.

defs.name: black_box
defs.docs:
A function that is opaque to the optimizer, used to prevent the compiler from
 optimizing away computations in a benchmark.
 
 This variant is stable-compatible, but it may cause some performance overhead
 or fail to prevent code from being eliminated.

defs.name: Fun
defs.docs:
Representing a function to benchmark together with a name of that function.
 Used together with `bench_functions` to represent one out of multiple functions
 under benchmark.

defs.name: new
defs.docs: Create a new `Fun` given a name and a closure

defs.name: Bencher
defs.docs: Helper struct to time routines

defs.name: iter
defs.value: fn <O, R> (&mut self, mut routine: R) -> ()
defs.docs: Times a `routine` by executing it many times and timing the total elapsed time.

defs.name: iter_with_setup
defs.value: fn <I, O, S, R> (&mut self, mut setup: S, mut routine: R) -> ()
defs.docs: Times a `routine` that requires some `setup` on each iteration.

defs.name: iter_with_large_drop
defs.value: fn <O, R> (&mut self, mut routine: R) -> ()
defs.docs:
Times a `routine` by collecting its output on each iteration. This avoids timing the
 destructor of the value returned by `routine`.

defs.name: iter_with_large_setup
defs.value: fn <I, S, R> (&mut self, mut setup: S, mut routine: R) -> ()
defs.docs: Times a `routine` that needs to consume its input by first creating a pool of inputs.
